> Hi Jorge,
>
> you can do this using the arguments rightcols and rightlabs (or leftcols
> and leftlabs). For example, take the first meta-analysis in the help file
> of metacont():
>
> data(Fleiss1993cont)
> # Meta-analysis with Hedges' g as effect measure
> #
> m1 <- metacont(n.psyc, mean.psyc, sd.psyc, n.cont, mean.cont, sd.cont,
>   data = Fleiss1993cont, sm = "SMD")
> rob <- LETTERS[1:5]                                         # Only as an
> example
> m1$rob <- rob                                                  # rob must
> be a part of the meta-analysis object
> forest(m1, rightcols = c("effect", "ci", "w.random", "rob"),
>   rightlabs = c("SMD", "95%-CI", "Weight (random)", "Risk of bias"))
>
> Note that the column names "effect", "ci", "w.random" are fixed names, as
> seen in the help of forest.meta().
